8 FIRST SPECIAL SESSION
9 COMMITTEE AMENDMENT “ ” to H.P. 1008, L.D. 1523, “An Act to Improve
10 Perinatal Care Through Expanded Access to Doula Services”
11 Amend the bill by striking out the title and substituting the following:
12 'Resolve, to Develop MaineCare Coverage for Doula Services'
13 Amend the bill by striking out everything after the title and inserting the following:
14 'Sec. 1. Rate determination for doula services. Resolved: That, no later than
15 January 1, 2026, the Department of Health and Human Services shall initiate a rate
16 determination process according to the requirements of the Maine Revised Statutes, Title
17 22, section 3173-J for the provision of doula services under the MaineCare program with a
18 planned start for reimbursement, subject to sufficient appropriations from the Legislature,
19 of January 1, 2028. For the purposes of this resolve, "doula services" means the provision
20 of services to a person by a nonclinical professional related to the physical, emotional and
21 informational support of that person throughout pregnancy, labor, birth and the postpartum
22 period, including, but not limited to, guidance and support concerning pregnancy health,
23 childbirth, infant feeding and newborn care.
24 Sec. 2. Doula council. Resolved: That the department shall establish a
25 multidisciplinary statewide doula council to provide advice and make recommendations to
26 the department regarding doula services, including consulting in the rate determination
27 process pursuant to section 1. The doula council must include practicing doulas. The doula
28 council must provide advice to the department on topics, including, but not limited to, the
29 scope of doula services that could become eligible for reimbursement under the MaineCare
30 program, appropriate credentials for doulas, strategies for recruiting a diverse workforce of
31 doulas to provide services in the State, reimbursement and billing issues and outreach to
32 the public about how to access doula services.
33 Sec. 3. Report. Resolved: That the department shall submit a report, no later than
34 February 1, 2027, to the joint standing committee of the Legislature having jurisdiction
35 over health and human services matters with the department's progress on developing rates
36 under section 1 and recommendations for reimbursement for doula services under the
